internal/tools/applypatch.go:55:			Description: "Apply a unified diff format patch to one or more files. Use this when you have a patch generated by git diff or a diff tool, and want to apply it programmatically. Supports multi-file patches atomically.\n\n**When to use**: Apply a unified diff patch to modify files. Ideal for applying code review suggestions, merging changes from external sources, or applying refactoring patches. Use when the edit tool is not suitable because you have a complete diff rather than knowing the exact strings to replace.\n\n**Parameters**:\n- `patch`: Unified diff format patch content. Must follow the standard unified diff format with ---/+++ headers and @@ hunk markers. Required.\n- `reverse` (optional): When true, reverses the patch (undoes the changes). Default is false.\n- `dry_run` (optional): When true, validates the patch without actually modifying any files. Useful to check if a patch will apply cleanly. Default is false.\n- `backup` (optional): When true, creates .patch.bak backup files before applying. Default is true (disabled only when dry_run or reverse is true).\n\n**Relationship to other tools**:\n- Use edit for single-file, targeted string replacements where you know the exact old and new text.\n- Use apply_patch when you have a unified diff patch or need to modify multiple files atomically.\n- apply_patch can apply hunks with fuzzy matching (context lines do not need to be exact), unlike edit which requires exact string match.\n\n**Safety constraints**:\n- Maximum patch size is 1MB to prevent memory issues.\n- Path traversal attacks (../etc/passwd) are blocked.\n- If any file in a multi-file patch fails to apply, all changes are rolled back.\n- Hunk context mismatch causes the patch application to fail (use dry_run to check first).\n\n**Output format**: Returns a summary of successfully patched files, or an error describing what failed. On failure, all changes are automatically rolled back.",
